Introduction

As we start on this tutorial, let me repeat some statements from p.57 of BC&P:

We advocate a very fundamental rule for data analysis. Never start an analysis with statistical analysis. Always start an analysis with a picture. Why? If you some expected/hypothesized theoretical relationship underpinned your research effort. You have in your head an expected pattern in your data. Plot your data first. Make the picture that should tell you the answer - make the axes correspond to the theory. If you can do this, and see the pattern you expected, you are in great shape. You will possibly know the answer!

We will explicitly follow this advice in class, and you should never fail to do so in your own work. In A First R Tutorial we learned and used the basic R function, plot(). That function will do a lot of work for us. If you are interested in seeing how one can use it, to do what we will now do, please look at:

 A. P. Beckerman and  Owen L. Petchey. 2012. Getting
started with R: An Introduction for Biologists.

The pdf of the chapters in this book are posted on our course Canvas website. As BC&P state in their Preface to the second edition:

Over the past five years much has changed R has evolved.Our changes and suggestions take of some new and very cool, efficient, and straightforward tools. We think these changes will help you focus even more on your data and questions. This is goodWe no longer rely on base [classic] R and graphics for data manipulation and figure making, instead introducingdplyr and ggplot2.

Please take the time to reread the Preface in BC&P.So now we will start learning and using a popular and new set of tools. in R. The classic set of base R tools, like plot() and aov(), are still there.
But these newer tools will be both easier to learn, use, and help those of you who may make more extensive use of R get a good start.

Histograms

Lets learn how to make a histogram of our data. Guess what we are going to use? Oh, you guessed it ggplot.

Use the lines below this comment to type the scripts in section 4.4 of BC&P as you read the text. We will learn how to create a histogram of the compensation data. We will discuss histograms in class, so do not worry if you have never seen one before. All will be revealed shortly!

Use the lines below this comment to type your script.

Do not forget to get help on the new functions that you encounter in these script segments. Do not enter the comments statements. Wait to see what R prints in the Console as well as the Plots tab.

ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Note

The number of bins used bins = 30 is the default. We can alter it. Isnt that nice? That ggplot is some kind of function (actually, the person who wrote the function was thinking about how to use the function. Thank you whoever you are!) Move on and enter the next lines of script and run them.

ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 10)

  ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 15)

Run the next lines of script.

ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 15) +
  facet_wrap(~Grazing)

Stop for a moment and this reflect on what we have just seen.Looking at the histograms that we have just asked ggplot to create gives us an important lesson. Histograms have a weakness that we have to be aware of before we use them. The shape of a histogram is dependent on the the number of bins and/or the bin size. Nothing is fool proof. That is just reality. the careful user must simply be aware of this.

Now lets use a feature in ggplot() that is really useful to a researcher or analysis. The idea of facets.

Q2. What is a facet? Do not simply enter the script in the text, stop and answer that question. A facet is.

A facet is a group within data. In this case grazed or ungrazed

ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 15) +
  facet_wrap(~Grazing)

WOW! A two-fer!! How easy was that?

Do not lose sight of the authors mentioning the ~ (tilda) and the increasing use of it as we continue learning how to use R.
Make sure that you can find the ~ on the keyboard of your computer.

Here it should be mentioned that plots with all that the authors of BC&P refer to as pimping can contain a great deal of information. That information takes computer memory to store. The R code itself takes very little memory. No matter how cheap computer memory is, it is still finite. So, as a general practice it is wiser to store the code that generates the plot and rerun the code whenever you need the plot rather than saving the plot.

Lets do all of this more completely below. You will notice that the authors start all over each time by writing the script

"ggplot(data = compensation, aes(.....))....",

but we have already gone to the trouble of assigning the output of ggplot(.) to an object.

Why not directly modify the object to which the plot was assigned? This is using the power of objects and it is how complete plot scripts are written. It is good to practice it. We will do that in the script segments below.

Run the entire script below, and you should get the plots in the text.

# Load libraries of functions
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

# Clear the memory
rm(list=ls())

compensation = read_csv("compensation.csv") # Load the desired data set
## Rows: 40 Columns: 3
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): Grazing
## dbl (2): Root, Fruit
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Generate a base scatterplot. Assign that plot to an object for later use in our script.

eg_scatter = ggplot(data = compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit, 
                                  color = Grazing)) + geom_point()

Generate a base box-and-whisker plot.Assign that plot to an object eg_box for later use.

eg_box =
  ggplot(data = compensation, aes(x = Grazing, y = Fruit)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Apply a black on a white background theme to the scatterplot object and some other features.

eg_scatter + theme_bw() +
  xlab("Root Biomass (appropriate units)") + 
  ylab("Fruit Production (Kg)") +
  ggtitle("Scatterplot of Fruit vs. Root Mass") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(4, 11), breaks = 4:11) + 
  ylim(0, 140) +
  annotate("text", x = c(6,8), y = c(105, 25),
           label = c("Text up here...","...and text down here")) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c(Grazed = "brown", Ungrazed =
                                   "green"))

Doing this in another way

eg_scatter + theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Fruit vs. Root Mass ",
       x = "Root Biomassb (appropriate units)", 
       y = "Fruit Production (Kg)") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(4, 11), breaks = 4:11) + 
  ylim(0, 140) +
  annotate("text", x = c(6,8), y = c(105, 25),
           label = c("Text up here...","...and text down here")) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c(Grazed = "brown", Ungrazed =
                                   "green"))

Arrange both plots on the one page.

grid.arrange(eg_scatter, eg_box, nrow = 1)

This is the end of the plotting script.

In the space at the end of these comments, go ahead and make the log transformation discussed on page 211. There is no need to do this in the complete code. Simply enter the script and run it. In this tutorial, we have learned to build a script that will create a fully formed plot without having to add modifying line of code to a base graph as BC&P have done. Please notice that BC&P have demonstrated adding advanced features to graphs by assigning a plot to an object and then modifying the object. Please notice just how useful objects are in R. Even a plot can become an object. Everything in R is an object, and R is just a collection of a large number of functions. That is one thing that makes R so powerful.

Yes, there is a good deal of syntax to learn in R (there is in all software), but if you forget some syntax, you can always look it up when you need it.

Before we end this tutorial consider two comments:

[1] Computers are controlled by microprocessors and these are physical devices that may incur errors. Software runs on microprocessors and it does not always do what you expect it to do, but it always does what it was programmed to do even if that was unintentional by the people that wrote the code. Go back and review section 2.4 (Basic troubleshooting while importing data).

[2] R does a lot, but it does not always do what you need. For those of you who believe that computer software will solve all of your quantitative problems, please consider the following from the FISH 559 website:

 "Most fisheries and other wildlife professionals 
  who are tasked with providing scientific advice 
  to decision makers often find existing software 
  tools insufficient for their needs, requiring 
  the development of purpose-built computer programs.
  Numerical techniques should not be applied "cookbook"
  style. It is necessary to understand the mathematical
  basis for the technique. Furthermore, numerical 
  techniques frequently involve expert judgment 
  regarding choices (e.g. for tolerances, initial values).
  The best way to learn a numerical technique therefore
  involves knowing its theoretical basis and spending 
  time practicing it.."

Please keep comment[2] in mind as we begin the study of statistics.
